===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|rifler||to scrape off, plunder|lang=fro}}, from [[Old Low Franconian]] *''riffilōn'' (compare obsolete {{etyl|nl|-}} ''rijffelen'' 'to scrape', {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|geriflian||to wrinkle|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|gmh|en}} {{term|riffeln||to scratch, heckle (flax)|lang=gmh}}, {{etyl|goh|en}} {{term|riffilōn||to saw, rub apart|lang=goh}}), frequentative of {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*rīfaną}} (compare {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|rifa||to tear, break|lang=non}}). More at {{term|rive|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈraɪfəl/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-rifle.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A long [[firearm]] firing a single projectile, usually with a [[rifled]] barrel to improve [[accuracy]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1907|author=[[w:Harold Edward Bindloss|Harold Bindloss]]
|title=The Dust of Conflict
|chapter=7|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL4429277W
|passage=Still, a dozen men with '''rifles''', and cartridges to match, stayed behind when they filed through a white aldea lying silent amid the cane, and the Sin Verguenza swung into slightly quicker stride.}}
# A [[strip]] of [[wood]] covered with [[emery]] or a similar material, used for [[sharpen]]ing [[scythe]]s.

